+à¿mchroma:documentDear Lamija,
Thank you for your message‚Äîand no worries at all, I completely understand! I hope you had a smooth and enjoyable time on the road.
I‚Äôm so happy to hear you‚Äôre excited about the confirmed date‚Äîit‚Äôs all becoming real now!
Thank you also for confirming your preferences regarding the additional services. Noted on that, and of course, if anything changes later on, feel free to let me know.
Regarding the apostille: it‚Äôs a great question. The only authority in Denmark that can issue an apostille is the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and they are located in Copenhagen. So, unfortunately, it‚Äôs not possible to get the apostille in Odense‚Äîit must be done in Copenhagen either in person or by post.
So if you have time to travel to Copenhagen after your wedding ceremony, HERE is the website of the legalisation page on the Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs website. You will find everything you need on this web page; open hours, address, how to access the legalisation office, contact information.
You will need to click through to the web shop to proceed. The web shop is where you pay for your Apostille stamp/s. You need to do this in advance of going to the Ministry, download your receipt after you have paid and make sure you take it with you when you go to the Ministry to obtain your stamp/s.
It is 235 DKK (approx. ‚Ç¨32) for each Apostille stamp on your Danish marriage certificate.
When you do go to the legalisation office at the Ministry to get the legalisation, you don't need to make an appointment or anything, you can just walk in. Join the queue and wait to be called. :-)
I hope this helps? For anything else, please just let us know!
Warmest regards,
Erma
\_\_
Erma
Your team at Getting Married in Denmark
