>> Dear Lamija and Francisco,
>> Now your date is firmly in the diary you can turn your attention to the finer details of your wedding in Denmark and also what may be required from you afterwards.
>> On that note, I wanted to give you some information about your marriage certificates.
>> Immediately after your wedding, once all the paperwork is signed, you will be given two Danish International Marriage Certificates.
>> Each certificate comes with the translation into the Danish, English, German, Spanish and French language.
>> Your wedding certificates are legal and binding but we do notice that sometimes couples come back to us after they have returned home to let us know that the authorities there have requested they obtain an Apostille stamp on their certificate.
>> We advise that you check with the office where you intend to use your certificate, to find out what (if any) legalisation they might require. Then you can be fully prepared.
>> If you are not sure, then it may be helpful to know that some couples get the Apostille stamp on one certificate, as a precaution, just in case it is needed.
>> Our Apostille service is designed to remove this bureaucratic process from your shoulders, and we will take care of it for you, after your wedding. It is ‚Ç¨250 for one certificate or ‚Ç¨285 for both.
>> Please let me know if this is something you might need or if you have any questions about anything at all.
>> Kindest Regards,
>> Erma
>> \_\_
